# Spec 010 — UI Refresh: National Defaults, Accessibility, Branding

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: 007-national-coverage (the scope the UI must catch up to),
009-zip-explorer (URL-state interplay), 005-frontend-resilience (toasts)

## Overview

The app is national and public, but the UI still behaves like the Seattle
MVP: the work pin defaults to a named Seattle landmark with a "Reset to
Museum of Flight" button, raw coordinates display in the panel, address
search is proximity-biased to Seattle for every visitor, copy is stale
("30-min" regardless of the time control), and there is no favicon, page
metadata, or brand presence. This spec nationalizes the defaults (including
a geolocated landing), regroups the crowded controls panel, fixes the
accessibility failures found in audit, and integrates the brand assets.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Geolocated landing.** On first load with NO recognized URL params,
  ask for browser geolocation (6 s timeout, cached fix ≤10 min, low
  accuracy). On success, map the point to a region (containing bbox; ties
  broken by distance to region center) and open it with the work pin at the
  visitor's location, silently. The WA default renders underneath and
  remains on deny/timeout/unsupported/no-match; a user interaction before
  the fix arrives cancels it. Any URL param skips geolocation entirely.
  (Accepts one extra upstream isochrone call per geolocated visit — bounded
  by 004's rate limit and daily budget.)
- **R2 — National defaults and copy.** No Seattle-specific names or raw
  coordinates anywhere in the UI: reset targets the selected state's
  center ("Reset to {State} center"); the work location reads as a place
  name (from address search), "{State} center", "Your location", or
  "Custom pin location" — never lat/lon; the footer reflects the selected
  commute minutes; region-failure copy and metro-label fallbacks derive
  from the actual selected state, not "Washington".
- **R3 — Client-supplied geocode proximity.** `/api/geocode` accepts
  optional validated `proximity_lat`/`proximity_lon` (±90/±180; used only
  when both present); the frontend sends the selected region's center.
  Without proximity the search is unbiased (still `country=us`). The
  geocode cache key includes the rounded proximity so per-region results
  never cross-contaminate. Token safety (001-R5) unchanged.
- **R4 — Panel grouping.** Core controls (region, budget, work, commute
  minutes, metric switcher, legend) stay always-visible with clear section
  separation; secondary content (Top movers, traffic-scenario breakdown)
  collapses behind native `<details>/<summary>` folds.
- **R5 — Accessibility.** All interactive targets ≥40 px effective height
  (≥44 px on coarse pointers); muted text meets 4.5:1 contrast; the
  over-budget legend swatch is visibly rendered (not 15% opacity); the page
  has exactly one h1 (visually hidden) with panel headings demoted; the
  address input shows the global focus-visible ring.
- **R6 — Branding and metadata.** Brand wordmark replaces the text title in
  the panel header and crash card; an SVG favicon (+ 180 px apple-touch
  PNG) derived from the brand; `index.html` gains a national title, meta
  description, theme-color, and absolute Open Graph/Twitter tags
  (`og:image` = the 1200×630 social image) pointing at
  https://tradespace-x5xj.onrender.com. Assets live in
  `frontend/public/brand/` as `logo.png`, `social.png`, `favicon.svg`,
  `apple-touch-icon.png`.

## Non-functional / Constraints

- No new runtime dependencies; geolocation is browser-native and never
  reaches the backend or any log (no-personal-data constraint holds — the
  coordinates only feed the existing work-pin flow a drag would).
- URL-state (009 R5) interplay: geolocation runs only when the parsed URL
  is empty; the debounced URL writer then serializes whatever state
  results, keeping deep links shareable.
- Existing MapView test exemption unchanged.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Fresh tab + allow location (DevTools sensor on Denver): Colorado
      opens, pin at the sensor location labeled "Your location", URL gains
      `?state=CO&lat=…`. Deny: Washington as today. `/?budget=500000`:
      no permission prompt.
- [ ] No "Seattle", "Museum of Flight", or raw coordinates appear anywhere
      in the UI; reset button names the selected state; footer tracks the
      minutes control.
- [ ] Address search while Texas is selected returns Texas matches for an
      ambiguous query (e.g. "Main St Springfield"-class queries bias local).
- [ ] Top movers and traffic scenarios collapse/expand; core controls fit
      a 390 px-wide sheet with materially less scrolling than before.
- [ ] Lighthouse accessibility: contrast and target-size audits pass;
      keyboard tab shows a visible ring on every control including the
      address input; exactly one h1 in the document.
- [ ] Browser tab shows the favicon; a shared link unfurls with title,
      description, and the social image; the panel header and crash card
      show the wordmark.
- [ ] `pytest` and `npm run test` pass with updated/new tests
      (geocode proximity + cache isolation, regionForPoint, useGeolocate,
      copy updates).

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- A designed 1200×630 social card (the app screenshot serves for now) and
  a true square brand mark (generated favicon until provided).
- Skip links; full panel redesign; custom domain.

